{{Infobox person | image = Kyle Datta Ulupono Initiative 2012.jpg | caption = Kyle Datta in 2012 | residence = [[Hawaii Island]], Hawaii, U.S. | occupation = General Partner of [[Ulupono Initiative]] | boards = Blue Planet Foundation, [[Parker Ranch]], Johnson Ohana Charitable Foundation }}
'''Kyle Datta''', who has been a General Partner of [[Ulupono Initiative]] since it was founded in 2009, announced today that he is retiring.
''“We are so grateful for all of Kyle’s work to help build Ulupono over the last decade,”'' said [http://ulupono.com/mike-mohr.html Mike Mohr], board member of Ulupono Initiative. ''“His strategic systems approach to tackling some of our state’s biggest challenges lays the foundation for transformative change to help Hawai‘i be more resilient and self-sufficient for many years to come. We wish him well and hope he enjoys his retirement.”''
During Datta’s tenure, Ulupono has invested nearly $80 million in organizations across the state that are working to increase the quality of life for Hawai‘i’s residents by producing more local food, generating more renewable energy, increasing clean transportation, and supporting better management of water and waste.
''“It has been such an honor for me to help start and guide Ulupono’s work,”'' Datta said. ''“I am deeply grateful for the confidence that the board has placed in me as well as for the remarkable colleagues and community partners I have had the privilege to work with over the years. While I have very much enjoyed my role with Ulupono, it’s time for me to take a step back, and I am confident about Ulupono’s ability to continue to have catalytic impact for Hawai‘i. I look forward to continuing my work with a variety of organizations throughout the state to help further Hawai‘i’s sustainability and resilience.”''
[http://ulupono.com/murray-clay.html Murray Clay] will continue as the [http://ulupono.com/murray-clay.html Managing Partner], overseeing all operations and investments.
<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ulupono.com/kyle-datta|title=Kyle Datta - Ulupono Initiative|website=ulupono.com|access-date=2016-03-15}}</ref> Previously, he was the CEO of U.S. Biodiesel Group, a national biodiesel firm funded by private equity; managing director of research and consulting at the [[Rocky Mountain Institute]]; and a vice president of [[Booz, Allen & Hamilton]], where he was the managing partner of the firm's Asia Energy Practice and later led the U.S. Utilities practice. Datta holds [[Bachelor of Science|bachelor of science]], master in [[environmental science]] in resource economics, and master in public and private management degrees from [[Yale University]]. He was CEO of New Energy Partners, an energy consulting and [[Renewable energy commercialization|renewable development]] firm located in [[Hawaii]]. He has co-authored several books including ''[[Winning the Oil Endgame]]'' (2005), and ''[[Small is Profitable]]'' (2002).<ref>[http://www.smallisprofitable.org/TheAuthors.html Small is Profitable: The authors]</ref>
Datta serves on the board of directors for [http://blueplanetfoundation.org/ Blue Planet Foundation], [http://www.bioenergyhawaii.com/ Hawaii BioEnergy], [http://johnsonohana.org/ Johnson Ohana Charitable Foundation], and [http://www.safsf.org/ Sustainable Agriculture and Food Systems Funders].
