'''Edinburgh Unemployed Workers Centre''', also called '''Broughton Unemployed Workers Centre''' or simply "'''The Centre'''", was an organisation set up by the local [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] in [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]], as a means of aiding the local unemployed find work in 1981.
However, it soon between independent from the Labour Party and individuals involved became prominent in various social movements of the period, including resistance to the [[Poll Tax (Great Britain)|Poll Tax]].{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} The Labour Party objected and the council inspected the building and it was shut down. Activists resisted its eviction by occupying the premises until December 1, 1994.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://libcom.org/library/auld-reekie-anarchy|title=Auld Reekie anarchy|website=libcom.org|access-date=2016-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://socialcentrestories.wordpress.com/2008/04/29/the-autonomous-centre-of-edinburgh/|title=The Autonomous Centre of Edinburgh|date=2008-04-29|access-date=2016-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.broughtonspurtle.org.uk/sites/broughtonspurtle.org.uk/files/Issue%203.pdf|title=Brougton Spurtle Issue 203|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> The Centre was frequently in the pages of the local paper, the ''Broughton [[Spurtle]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.broughtonspurtle.org.uk/sites/broughtonspurtle.org.uk/files/Issue%202.pdf|title=Broughton Spurtle Issue 202|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> The Centre was home to Edinburgh claimants during this period. The collective associated with the Centre was the precursor to what was to become the [[Autonomous Centre of Edinburgh]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://autonomous.org.uk/history-of-ace/|title=History of ACE - The Autonomous Centre of Edinburgh|newspaper=The Autonomous Centre of Edinburgh|language=en-US|access-date=2016-12-16}}</ref>
The Edinburgh poet Paul Reekie wrote a poem, "Kiss ma hole",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://srl.autonomous.org.uk/?p=71|title=Counterinfo Lab – Kiss ma hole: autonomous struggles in Scottish politics and culture {{!}} Scottish Radical Library|website=srl.autonomous.org.uk|access-date=2016-12-16}}</ref> dedicated to the Centre and the [[Glasgow|Glaswegian]] writer [[James Kelman]] gave a speech at its opening.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DMq8BQAAQBAJ&pg=PT68|title=And the Judges Said&…: Essays|last=Kelman|first=James|date=2012-08-10|publisher=Birlinn|isbn=9780857901415|language=en}}</ref>
