The '''Herzegovina lobby''' or '''Herzegovinian lobby''' ([[Bosnian language|Bosnian]] and {{lang-hr|Hercegovački lobi}}) is a disputed term that emerged in [[Croatia]] in the 1990s{{sfn|Dodig|2005|p=144}} for the alleged disproportional influence of [[Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Croats]] from the [[Herzegovina]] region of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] on the politics of Croatia.{{sfn|Večernji list|1 July 2005}} At times it has been described it as a major factor in contemporary Croatian politics{{sfn|Toal|Dahlman|2011|p=63}} and the most powerful lobby in Croatia,{{sfn|Cvijetić|31 January 2000}} it is also viewed as a [[stereotype]],{{sfn|Katuranić|1995|p=267}} pejorative,{{sfn|Zarez|4 February 2010}} and nonexistent.{{sfn|Večernji list|1 July 2005}}
Proponents of the existence of such a lobby claim that it helped fund Croatia's war-time president [[Franjo Tuđman]], his [[Croatian Democratic Union]] (HDZ) political party, and his involvement in the [[Bosnian War]], during which the lobby openly advocated annexing Herzegovina.{{sfn|Saideman|Ayres|2012|pp=64-6}} During the Bosnian War, Croats in Herzegovina, were more interested in unifying with Croatia than being a part of an independent [[Bosniak]]-dominated Bosnia and Herzegovina. Due to the strength of the Herzegovina lobby in [[Zagreb]], moderate Bosnian Croats were mostly ineffective in influencing Croatian foreign policy on Bosnia and Herzegovina. Many extremists from Herzegovina served in the Croatian police force and to participate in [[Log Revolution|skirmishes]] with Serbs.{{sfn|Saideman|Ayres|2012|pp=64-6}} By late 1991 about 20,000 Croats in Bosnia and Herzegovina, mostly from the Herzegovina region, enlisted in the [[Croatian National Guard]].{{sfn|Hockenos|2003|pp=91-2}}
The Herzegovina lobby's bonding in Croatia began with Tuđman's ouster of [[Stjepan Kljuić]], the moderate and independent elected leader of the Bosnian branch of the HDZ, and replacement with [[Mate Boban]].{{sfn|Lampe|2000|p=376}}{{sfn|Gow|1997|p=82}}{{sfn|Toal|Dahlman|2011|p=68}} Boban, who favored Croatia to annex Croat-inhabited parts of Bosnia and Herzegovina,{{sfn|Ramet|2006|p=343}}{{sfn|Tanner|2001|p=286}} was in charge of advancing the lobby's agenda in Bosnia and Herzegovina.{{sfn|Toal|Dahlman|2011|p=103}} A rift existed in the HDZ between Croats from ethnically mixed areas of central and northern Bosnia and those from Herzegovina.{{sfn|Hockenos|2003|p=92}} After Croats in Bosnia and Herzegovina gained the ability to vote in Croatia's elections they played a growing role in the country's politics.{{sfn|Saideman|Ayres|2012|pp=64-6}} The approximately 365,000 Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina consistently voted for the HDZ.{{sfn|Bellamy|2003|p=73}} In the 1994 elections, the Croatian diaspora received twelve to fourteen of the 164 seats in the [[Croatian Parliament]], significantly larger than its share of Croatia's population.{{sfn|Saideman|Ayres|2012|pp=64-6}} The lobby was accused of behaving in a Mafia-like manner due to their corruption and violence in Croatia.{{sfn|Bellamy|2003|p=93}}
[[Gojko Šušak]], who believed in a [[Greater Croatia]],{{sfn|Toal|Dahlman|2011|p=63}} played a vital role in funding the HDZ.{{sfn|Søberg|2007|p=59}} He was considered the leader of the Herzegovina lobby{{sfn|Kifner|3 January 1994}}{{sfn|Hedl|16 November 2005}} and was "adept at tapping the purses of the tight-knit Herzegovinian community in the Americas, delivering millions of dollars worth of contributions to Tuđman's campaign." He provided the HDZ a critical advantage over the political opposition and for his efforts became the [[Croatian Minister of Defence]].{{sfn|Saideman|Ayres|2012|p=64}} Several other top positions within the HDZ government were also secured.{{sfn|Bellamy|2003|p=72}} In his position he protected and promoted generals from Herzegovina in the Croatian Army{{sfn|Lukić|2008|p=208}} and acted as a "conduit" of Croatian support for Croat separatism in Bosnia and Herzegovina.{{sfn|Hoare|2010|p=128}} At its peak the amount of money from Croatia that funded the [[Croatian Defence Council]] surpassed $500,000 per day.{{sfn|Ramet|2010|p=265}} After Šušak's death in 1998, [[Ivić Pašalić]] took over as head of the lobby.{{sfn|BBC|11 December 1999}} By 2000, about 300 million euros were transferred by the Croatian government into Herzegovina each year, mostly from the budget of the Ministries of Defence, Reconstruction, and Social Affairs.{{sfn|Grandits|2016|pp=107-8}}
The existence of such a lobby has been widely criticized and described as a [[conspiracy theory]],{{sfn|Sadkovich|2010|pp=247}} as it "never existed, but was created as a figment of someone's imagination and the belief that the politicians in Zagreb originating from Herzegovina aided their homeland."{{sfn|Večernji list|1 July 2005}} Croatian-American historian James J. Sadkovich wrote that "claims that the Croatian president was manipulated by Šušak and a "Herzegovina lobby" are as difficult to document as allegations that the Croatian diaspora made HDZ policy."{{sfn|Sadkovich|2007|pp=217}} After the international recognition of Croatia in January 1992, the Herzegovinian identity in some media worsened and stereotype views were promoted.{{sfn|Dodig|2005|p=144}} Political opponents of Tuđman spread animosity towards Herzegovina and Herzegovinians. After a failed coup by [[Stjepan Mesić]] and [[Josip Manolić]] in the HDZ in 1993, Manolić accused the "Herzegovina lobby" for everything wrong in the party.{{sfn|Lučić|2005|p=58-59}} Such views were fueled by the weekly [[Feral Tribune]] which denigrated Herzegovina in its texts.{{sfn|Lučić|2005|p=63}} The anti-Herzegovinian hysteria reached a culmination on the eve and aftermath of the [[Croatian parliamentary election, 2000|2000 parliamentary election]].{{sfn|Večernji list|12 July 2006}} However, after 2000 the imposed stereotypes and usage of the term decreased.{{sfn|Dodig|2005|p=144}}
