{{Infobox school | name = Solomon Mahlangu Freedom College | image = | alt = | caption = | motto = | location = Mazimbu, [[Morogoro]] | country = [[Tanzania]] | coordinates = {{coord|06|51|10.85|S|37|39|26.85|E|display=inline,title}} | established = 1978 | opened = 1985 | closed = 9 September 1992 | type = | district = | grades = 1 - 12 | superintendent = | principal = Alpheus Mangezi | enrollment = | faculty = | campus_type = | campus_size = | team_name = | newspaper = | colors = | communities = | feeders = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | footnotes = }}
The '''Solomon Mahlangu Freedom College''' (SOMAFCO), was an educational institution established by the exiled [[African National Congress]] (ANC) in 1978 at Mazimbu, [[Tanzania]]. Its purpose was to give the youth that had fled South Africa after the 1976 [[Soweto uprising]] and children of existing exiles a primary and secondary education, an alternative to traditional [[Bantu Education Act, 1953|Bantu education system]] they would have received at home. It would teach both an academic and vocational education. Farmlands would supply food to the institution and would also include a hospital. It was officially opened by [[Oliver Tambo]] in 1985.
== History == The ANC's would establish its educational centre in [[Morogoro]], Tanzania on land donated by the Tanzanian government during 1977, facilitated by Tanzanian [[Anna Abdallah]].<ref name="Lodge">{{Cite journal |last=Lodge |first=Tom |date=1987 |title=State of Exile: The African National Congress of South Africa, 1976-86 |journal=Third World Quarterly |volume=9 |issue=1 |pages=1–27 |jstor=3991845 |registration=yes}}</ref>{{rp|11}}<ref name=Maaba/>{{rp|291}} The land at Mazimba, consisted of some farm buildings on 600 acres.<ref name="Lodge" />{{rp|11}} The school would be named after the [[Solomon Mahlangu]], a member of the ANC's military wing, [[Umkhonto we Sizwe]] (MK) and an exile of the 1976 [[Soweto uprising]].<ref name="Maaba">{{cite journal |last=Maaba |first=Brown Bavusile |title=Alternative Schooling for South Africans: Notes on the Solomon Mahlangu Freedom College in Tanzania, 1978-1992 |journal=The International Journal of African Historical Studies |volume=37 |issue=2 |pages=289–308 |jstor=4129010 |date=2004 |registration=yes|doi=10.2307/4129010 }}</ref>{{rp|289}} Other names that had been suggested for the school before settled on the existing name where the Albert Luthuli Institute and the ANC Freedom School.<ref name=Morrow/>{{rp|13}}
The complex was built by Oswald Dennis, an ANC civil engineer trained in [[East Germany]].<ref name=Maaba/>{{rp|290}} He would later be supported by architect Spenser Hodgson.<ref name=Morrow/>{{rp|19}} Work started in July 1977, built by Tanzanian labourers and supervised by the ANC, while education began under trees or in the existing farm buildings.<ref name=Maaba/>{{rp|290}} Eventually around eighty percent of the workforce would be made of Tanzanians.<ref name=Maaba/>{{rp|290}} As this would be a boarding school, accommodation was required and so six units catering for 144 pupils were built, with eight students per room.<ref name=Maaba/>{{rp|290}} The first dormitory was completed for occupation in late 1979 by pupils and teachers.<ref name=Morrow/>{{rp|20}} By 1980, the land had been cleared, existing houses on the land renovated, a temporary water supply and sewage system in place and the buildings linked to the local electricity network.<ref name=Morrow/>{{rp|21}} Future plans called for more dormitories, houses, kitchen and dining rooms as well as a library.<ref name=Morrow/>{{rp|22}}
Initially the plan for the facility was for a [[secondary school]] for exiles of the 1976 Soweto uprising and children of the pre-1976, but soon a [[Kindergarten|pre-primary school]] was established and by 1984 it would be formally called the [[Charlotte Maxeke]] Children's Centre.<ref name="Donge">{{Cite journal |last=van Donge |first=Jan Kees |title=Review: Education in Exile: SOMAFCO, the ANC School in Tanzania 1978-1992 by Sean Morrow; Brown Maaba; Loyiso Pulumani |journal=The Journal of Modern African Studies |volume=43 |issue=3 |pages=501–2 |jstor=3876072 | date=September 2005}}</ref>{{rp|501}}<ref name=Plaice/>{{rp|276}}<ref name=Morrow/>{{rp|11}} The centre started in the late 70's as a [[Day care|crèche]], first in the town itself before being moved back into a renovated house at SOMAFCO in 1981 as a crèche and [[Preschool|nursery school]].<ref name=Morrow/>{{rp|42}} The centre would open in 1984, built by Oswald Dennis from money supplied by the [[Swedish Teachers' Union]].<ref name=Morrow/>{{rp|42}}
By 1985 a [[primary school]] was formally established.<ref name=Plaice/>{{rp|276}}<ref name=Morrow/>{{rp|42}} In 1980, New Zealanders Terry and Barbara Bell arrived in Tanzania to establish the primary school which operated out of one of the renovated houses though overcrowding meant some had to attend primary school in town.<ref name=Morrow/>{{rp|51}} All teaching occurred in English.<ref name=Morrow/>{{rp|52}} The Bell's left in 1982 after clashing over the style of the school management. Dennis and Hazel September took over the management of the primary school and the style of teaching changed to a more conventional one of grade and performance measures.<ref name=Morrow/>{{rp|57}}
Food for the facility was supplied from the farms' land which would supply milk, eggs, pork, beef and maize.<ref name=Maaba/>{{rp|291}} Hans Jurgen's expertise as an agricultural consultant would provided by the [[Swedish International Development Cooperation Agency]].<ref name=Morrow/>{{rp|23}} He would set about constructing a farm plan to make the facility self-sufficient by 1984 for 2,500 residents.<ref name=Morrow/>{{rp|23–4}} Teachers and students were expected spend a time each week working on the farms.<ref name="Lodge" />{{rp|13}} Security for the complex was provided by the [[Tanzania People's Defence Force]].<ref name=Maaba/> {{rp|291}}
Medical issues were initially conducted by a clinic at the institution but when politics and personal issues took hold there in the early eighties and with the increase in the need to supply more sophisticated medical treatments, the ANC decided that a hospital should be built.<ref name=Morrow/>{{rp|24–6}} Later called the ANC-Holland Solidarity Hospital, it was opened on 1 May 1984.<ref name=Morrow/>{{rp|26}} A solidarity group in the [[Netherlands]] under Henk Odenk would finance it and the ANC was responsible for its construction.<ref name=Morrow/>{{rp|27}}
The furniture factory was financed out of Finland and would open in 1980 and was called the Vuyisile Mini Furniture Factory, named after [[Vuyisile Mini]] an executed MK soldier.<ref name=Morrow/>{{rp|26}} In addition to repairing broken furniture it would supply the building projects with doors, window frames and furniture.<ref name=Morrow/>{{rp|27}}
== Teaching and curriculum == Teachers where recruited from three main sources. Firstly from ANC members with professional qualifications, secondly from matriculated members of the organisation and lastly overseas volunteer teachers who supported the aims of the ANC.<ref name=Morrow/>{{rp|29–30}} The ANC wished to emphasise the teaching of what it called the hard sciences, subjects such as science and biology, subjects that were not regularly taught to black pupils in South Africa under the governments [[Bantu Education Act, 1953|Bantu Education]] policy and which there was a shortage of amongst its own teachers.<ref name=Morrow/>{{rp|30}} The source of teachers would initially come from Europe such as the United Kingdom, Nordic countries, the Netherlands and GDR and then later from Nigeria, Zambia and Tanzania.<ref name=Morrow/>{{rp|30}}
The students were educated only in English, with both a traditional non-Bantu education and political education.<ref name=Maaba/>{{rp|292}} Subjects by the late 80's included English, Maths, History, Geography, Chemistry, Biology, Physics, Agricultural Science, Typing, Integrated Science, Technical drawing, Development of Societies, Literature and History of the Struggle.<ref name=Maaba/>{{rp|292}} The latter three were examined internally with the other subjects examined externally in the UK as [[General Certificate of Education|GCE]] O level examinations.<ref name=Maaba/>{{rp|292}} The secondary school consisted of six forms or grades and classes took place from Monday to Friday with a uniform worn though not strictly enforced.<ref name=Morrow/>{{rp|63–4}} Corporal punishment though not officially allowed did occur from time to time and depended on the teacher concerned.<ref name=Morrow/>{{rp|67}}
Tertiary education was not conducted by the college but through means of scholarships, worthy candidates received further education in British, European and American universities while Communist countries also assisted but mainly in the spheres of agriculture, paramedical workers and engineers as well as other technical skills.<ref name="Lodge" />{{rp|13}}
