== Financial backers == The Solomon Mahlangu Freedom College would receive its funds from foreign donors.<ref name="Lodge" />{{rp|13}} Most of the ANCs Scandinavian countries donations went into education with [[Norway]] and [[Sweden]] contributing $12 million in 1985 and $25 million by 1988.<ref name="Lodge" />{{rp|13}} The latter's aid was provided by the Swedish International Developmental Cooperation Agency.<ref name="Taylor">{{cite journal |last=Taylor |first=Ian |title=Review: Sweden and National Liberation in Southern Africa. Volume II: Solidarity and Assistance 1970-1994 by Tor Sellström |journal=International Affairs |volume=78 |issue=4 |pages=939 |jstor=3095807 |date=October 2002 |registration=yes}}</ref>{{rp|939}} Other donations for the work came from the [[German Democratic Republic]], [[Soviet Union]], [[United Nations Development Programme]], [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) solidarity organisations and individuals.<ref name=Maaba/>{{rp|290}}
== Closure == On its closure on 9 September 1992, the educational complex consisted of a pre-primary, primary and secondary school, the farm, furniture factory and other support units.<ref name="Morrow">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=tgU64zlZY54C&printsec=frontcover&dq=Solomon+Mahlangu+Freedom+College#v=onepage&q=Solomon%20Mahlangu%20Freedom%20College&f=false |title=Education in Exile: SOMAFCO, the African National Congress School in Tanzania, 1978 to 1992 |last=Morrow |first=Sean |last2=Maaba |first2=Brown |last3=Pulumani |first3=Loyiso |publisher=HSRC Press |year=2004 |isbn=9780796920515 |page=218}}</ref><ref name=Maaba/>{{rp|289}} The infrastructure that remained behind was integrated into the [[Sokoine University of Agriculture]].<ref name="Plaice">{{cite journal |last=Plaice |first=Evie |title=Review: Education in Exile: SOMAFCO, the ANC School in Tanzania, 1978 to 1992 by Seán Morrow; Brown Maaba; Loyiso Pulumani |journal=Comparative Education Review |volume=49 |issue=2 |pages=275–277 |jstor=10.1086/431163 |date=May 2005 |registration=yes|doi=10.1086/431163 }}</ref>{{rp|276}} In 1991, the National Co-ordinating Committee on for the Return of Exiles set up the Batlagae Trust, who through the means of bursaries, would integrate the school's pupils back into the South African education system on their return to the country.<ref name=Morrow/>{{rp|vii}}
The school's archives now rest at the [[University of Fort Hare]].<ref name=Plaice/>{{rp|277}} The documents began to arrive in September 1992 and stored in Centre for Cultural Studies before being moved to the Howard Pim Library in 1995.<ref name="Stapleton">{{cite journal |last1=Stapleton |first1=T.J. |last2=Maamoe |first2=M. |title=An Overview of the African National Congress Archives at the University of Fort Hare |journal=History in Africa |volume=25 |issue= |pages=413–422 |jstor=3172197 |date=1998 |registration=yes|doi=10.2307/3172197 }}</ref>{{rp|414}}
