'''Walter T. Brown''' (b. Aug 1937) is a [[young Earth creationist]], who is the director of his own ministry called the Center for Scientific Creation. ''[[The Skeptic's Dictionary]]'' considers him to be one of the leaders of the [[creation science]] movement.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://skepdic.com/creation.html |chapter=Creationism and creation science|title=The Skeptics Dictionary: A Collection of Strange Beliefs, Amusing Deceptions, and Dangerous Delusions|first=Robert Todd |last=Carroll|publisher= Wiley|edition= 1st|date=August 15, 2003 |isbn=0-471-27242-6|ref=harv}}</ref> He proposes a specific version of [[flood geology]] called the Hydroplate Theory. He is a retired army officer with a degree in mechanical engineering.
== Biography == Brown has a [[Ph.D.]] in [[mechanical engineering]] from the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], a B.S. from [[West Point]] and he served as an officer in the [[Military of the United States of America|United States military]] until he retired in 1980.<ref name="online edition">"About the Author," ''Center for Scientific Creation'', ''In the Beginning: Compelling Evidence for Creation and the Flood (7th ed.)'' ([http://www.creationscience.com/onlinebook/ online edition]). Accessed 27 December 2007. {{ISBN|1-932307-22-2}}</ref>
Since retiring from the military in 1980, Brown has been the director of his "Center for Scientific Creation" and has done his own research, writing, and speaking on origins theory.<ref name="online edition" /> In 1998, Brown was appointed to a committee reviewing Arizona's state science standards. Evolution was retained in the Arizona state science standards after a final decision in August 1998.<ref>[http://jinnetics.tripod.com/sp.html ''Evolution education now added to state high school standards''], Jayson Peters [[Arizona State University]] [[State Press]], Aug. 25, 1998</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://acept.asu.edu/news/newsletter/vol3/rissing.html |author=Steve Rissing |title=Evolution Included Into the Arizona Science Standards|publisher=ACEPT Newsletter, Volume 3 Spring 1999 |accessdate=2008-01-10 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010515142029/http://acept.asu.edu:80/news/newsletter/vol3/rissing.html |archivedate=May 15, 2001 |df= }}</ref>
==Hydroplate Theory== In Brown's ''In the Beginning: Compelling Evidence for Creation and the Flood'' he suggests evidence against [[evolution]] and for [[creation science]] and [[flood geology]] (including [[hydroplates]]). It is divided into three sections, the first of which explores discoveries made by scientists that do not fit the theory of [[evolution]].<ref>[http://www.creationscience.com/onlinebook/LifeSciences8.html CreationScience.com{{spaced ndash}}5. Natural Selection]</ref>{{Failed verification|date=July 2015}} The second section outlines various alternate explanations to geological and astronomical subjects such as the [[mid-oceanic ridge]] and [[comet]]s, which Brown states evolutionary science cannot explain. The final section presents a variety of other questions encountered in the [[creation-evolution controversy]].
In 1989, the Creation/Evolution journal of the National Center for Science Education published a critique of Brown's theory. [[Jim Lippard]], graduate student of philosophy begins with a criticism focusing primarily on fossil evidence of [[human evolution]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://ncse.com/cej/9/1/examination-research-creationist-walter-brown | title = An Examination of the Research of Creationist Walter Brown | last = Lippard | first = Jim | publisher = [[National Center for Science Education]] Creation/Evolution Journal | volume = 9 | issue = 25 | date = Fall 1989 | accessdate = 2009-02-24
}}</ref> Brown addressed several of Lippard's points in his response,<ref>{{cite news | url = http://ncse.com/cej/9/1/brown-responds-to-lippard | title = Brown Responds to Lippard | last = Brown | first = Walter T., Jr. | publisher = [[National Center for Science Education]] Creation/Evolution Journal | volume = 9 | issue = 25 | date = Fall 1989 | accessdate = 2009-02-24
}}</ref> and three further articles were printed: Lippard,<ref>{{cite news | url = http://ncse.com/cej/9/2/further-examination-research-walter-brown | title = A Further Examination of the Research of Walter Brown | last = Lippard | first = Jim | publisher = [[National Center for Science Education]] Creation/Evolution Journal | volume = 9 | issue = 26 | date = Winter 1989–1990 | accessdate = 2009-02-24
}}</ref> Brown,<ref name=brownresp2 >{{cite news | url = http://ncse.com/cej/9/2/second-response-to-jim-lippard | title = A Second Response to Jim Lippard | last = Brown | first = Walter T., Jr. | publisher = [[National Center for Science Education]] Creation/Evolution Journal | volume = 9 | issue = 26 | date = Winter 1989–1990 | accessdate = 2009-02-24
}}</ref> and ending with Lippard, where he asserts that Brown made serious errors, including using "mistaken claims about what others have written."<ref name=lippard >{{cite news | url = http://ncse.com/cej/10/1/final-response-to-walter-brown | title = A Final Response to Walter Brown | last = Lippard | first = Jim | publisher = [[National Center for Science Education]] Creation/Evolution Journal | volume = 10 | issue = 27 | date = Summer 1990 | accessdate = 2009-02-24
}}</ref> The series of articles does not discuss Brown's [[hydroplates|Hydroplate Theory]], apart from Brown's claim that Lippard "dismisses or ignores the bulk of the book and specifically addresses only a very small fraction of its substance."<ref name="brownresp2 " />
[[Robert T. Pennock]] has described Brown's position as being typical, other than the unique feature of his hydroplates hypothesis, of young-earth creationist's explaining all major terrestrial features in terms of a [[Catastrophism|catastrophic]] [[Flood geology|Biblical flood]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Pennock | first = Robert T. | authorlink = Robert T. Pennock | title = Tower of Babel: The Evidence Against the New Creationism | publisher = The MIT Press | date = February 28, 2000 | isbn = 0-262-66111-X | page = 13 }}</ref>
==Reception==
Walt Brown has had contentious relations with other creationist organizations.<ref>[[talkorigins.org]] [http://www.talkorigins.org/faqs/homs/wbdebateoffer.html ''Walter Brown's Debate Offer'']</ref><ref name=to>[http://www.talkorigins.org/faqs/homs/wbrown2.html ''More on Walter Brown's debate offer''], [[Jim Foley]], [[TalkOrigins]], September 30, 2004</ref> [[Answers in Genesis]] has a standing offer to Brown to publish some of his material in their journals<ref>[http://www.creationontheweb.com/content/view/2571/ ''Maintaining Creationist Integrity: A response to Kent Hovind''], [[Carl Wieland]], [[Ken Ham]] and [[Jonathan Sarfati]], [[Creation Ministries International]] [[website]], 11 October 2002 updated 16 December 2002 and 2 August 2006</ref> but Brown has declined.<ref name=to/> The [[old earth creationist]] organization [[Answers in Creation]] has published material rebutting Brown's hydroplate theory.<ref>[http://www.answersincreation.org/walter_brown_hydroplate_theory.htm ''Creation Science Rebuttals: Center for Scientific Creationism Walter Brown's Hydroplate Model''], [[Glenn R. Morton]], [[Answers in Creation]] [[website]], copyright 2003</ref> The [[Christian]] [[American Scientific Affiliation]] website features a video critical of Brown's video "God's Power and Scriptures Authority" by Steven H. Schimmrich of [[Kutztown University]].<ref>[http://www.asa3.org/archive/asa/199803/0079.html ''Re: Walter Brown Jr. Video''], [[Steven Schimmrich]], [[American Scientific Affiliation]], March 9, 1998</ref>
Brown has stated that no "[[evolutionist]]" will publicly debate with him,<ref>[http://www.cbn.com/cbnnews/275993.aspx ''The Global Flood as You've Never Seen It''], [[Christian Broadcasting Network]] News, 30 November 2007. Accessed 27 December 2007.</ref> but has been accused by opponents of complicating such debates.<ref name=to/><ref>[http://www.talkorigins.org/faqs/homs/wbrown.html ''Fossil Hominids: Response to In the Beginning''], Jim Foley, [[TalkOrigins]] [[website]], February 21, 2002</ref><ref>[http://www.talkorigins.org/indexcc/CA/CA342.html Claim CA342], [[Mark Isaak]], Index to Creationist Claims, [[TalkOrigins]], Copyright © 2004</ref> An abortive attempt at such a debate was held in 1989 and 1990 in the pages of Creation/Evolution, the [[National Center for Science Education]] journal, before Brown refused to continue.<ref name=lippard/> [[Joe Meert]] of ''[[Gondwana Research]]'', a journal promoting research related to the origin and evolution of [[continent]]s, alleges he "signed a contract" for such a debate with Brown in 2000. He claims Brown disputed the terms of the contract and it did not take place.<ref>[http://gondwanaresearch.com/hp/walt_brown.htm Walt Brown's Pseudochallenge], Joe Meert, [http://www.gondwanaresearchonline.com/General/Index.aspx Gondwana Research] website, updated March 26, 2006</ref> Brown stated on his website that the actual reason for the debate not taking place was that the Meert wanted to add religion and since Dr. Brown is not a theologian, he wanted the debate to be strictly science.<ref>[http://www.creationscience.com/onlinebook/index.html ''Center for Scientific Creation - Written Debate'']</ref> According to [[Georgia State University]] biology professor Fred K. Parrish, who afterwards claimed he was "tricked" into an April 1985 public debate with Brown, claims Brown has a set of preconditions (such as Brown speaks first, the debate moderator sits on his side, and all debate material would be scientific, not religious in nature).<ref>[http://ncse.com/cej/8/1/i-was-suckered-into-debate-survived ''I Was Suckered Into A Debate—And Survived!''], Fred K. Parrish, Creation/Evolution, XXII, 1988.</ref>
